Neither routine hematology nor CSF analysis is specific for this disorder. MRI of the brain (Figure 27-12
) may show parasitic track lesions, as well as cerebrocortical degeneration caused by toxin release by the parasite.34 Grossly, marked atrophy of the affected cerebral hemisphere can be apparent (Figure 27-13
). Vasospasm secondary to release of toxin produced by the parasite results in infarction in the region perfused by the middle cerebral artery or its branches.34
